considerations, including the career of Bruce Lee, Chinese wuxia films, and Don DeLillo's novel Running Dog. Ethnographies explored describe how the social body trains in martial arts and how martial arts are constructed in transnational training. Ultimately, this academic study of martial arts offers a focal point for new understandings of cultural and social beliefs and of practice and agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMartial arts -- Social aspects. 0aMartial artsxSocial aspects. 0aMartial arts. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aSociology : Sports and Society. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Martial Arts & Self-Defense.2bisacsh1 aBowman, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrer, D. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrer, D. S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLu, Jie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRennesson, Stéphane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelton, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhalen-Bridge, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhalen-Bridge, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 ade Grave, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438439686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isb